\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Homeownership and mobility are negatively correlated.
 In particular in times of significant drops in house prices, the issues
 surrounding homeowners who are reluctant to leave their home behind become
 more salient both in popular and academic press.
 Migration and ownership decisions have a strong lifecycle component, in
 the sense that individuals move more while young and buy houses as they
 get older (which means they get wealthier and have children).
 I propose a lifecycle model of migration between US census divisions where
 individuals decide to become owners and where frictions in the housing
 market and high moving costs imply that they are less likely to move in
 response to local income or house price shocks, over and above a generally
 declining propensity to move over their lifespan.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The annual aggregate mobility rate across census divisions is roughly 1.15%
 of the population, and it factors as 2.12% for renters and 0.67% for owners.
 These are large differences, and there are two sets of questions that wait
 to be asked in this context.
 Firstly, what are the implications of housing policies which subsidize
 homeownership for labor market mobility? For example, what is the elasticity
 of mobility with respect to the amount of mortgage interest that may be
 deducted from income tax, an important part of US housing policy? Secondly,
 what are the properties of housing and migration as insurance devices in
 this context, i.e.
 what is the net insurance value of homeownership, given that on the one
 hand owning provides insurance against rental price risk, but on the other
 seems to hinder insurance against labor market shocks, since moving becomes
 more difficult? In this paper I will attempt to provide answers to both
 sets of questions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why do we observe owners moving less? One answer to this question is that,
 particular in times of falling house prices, owners may have a sustantial
 amount of negative equity in the home, and they may feel obliged to stay
 put until prices recover so that any mortgage debt can be paid off, or
 simply because they lack the necessary funds to afford a downpayment for
 a new home elsewhere and they have a strong preference for owning.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
They feel obliged to repay rather than willing to default on the mortgage
 contract.
 See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "guiso2009moral"

\end_inset

 for a discussion.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Another answer could be that all else equal, owners face higher costs of
 effort when moving because they have to spend time finding a suitable buyer
 and meet with agents and lawyers and so forth -- in short, things a comparable
 renter does not have to contemplate.
 A third answer could be that they move less because they chose to stay,
 cementing their resolve, so to speak, by investing in owner--occupied property
 in a given location, based on the expectation of staying in that particular
 location for a number of years.
 It seems plausible to think that ownership and migration decisions are
 made jointly, at least in part driven by a preference for some location.
 My model incorporates all of the above mentioned mechanisms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The observed time series of house prices and median incomes in the nine
 census divisions are hard to generate from within a model over the period
 of observation (1996--2012).
 For this reason, the model simulation takes them as the real data as input,
 in a bid to recreate the incentives faced by individuals in the data as
 closely as possible.
 At the heart of much of the migration literature, as well as in this model,
 lies a tension between expected incomes and house prices in a potential
 destination location, such that high income regions attract more people,
 which subsequently drives up house prices because of inelastic housing
 supply, so that ultimately moving becomes less attractive.
 It is important to accurately represent the house price and income processes
 found in the data inside the model in order to get the relative desireability
 of regions right.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the model there is a simple mechanism that endogenously selects individuals
 into either renter or owner--occupied sector.
 Faced with idiosyncratic persistent uncertainty regarding their labor income,
 as well as a fluctuating house price, only individuals who satisfy a standard
 downpayment requirement are eligible to buy a house.
 Given that income increases on average over the lifecycle and depending
 on the path their individual income shocks have taken, it will in general
 take several years of assets accumulation before this constraint is satisfied.
 Not all individuals will buy a house once the constraint is satisfied,
 however, since this decision interacts with a preference for the current
 location.
 Buying has implications for future mobility, as we remarked previously,
 it has the potential to expose the owner to substantial financial risk
 in case of a price drop, therefore people with a higher preference for
 the location will be more likely to end up buying.
 The utility they gain from being in a given location compensates them for
 potential losses, should the need to move arise in the future.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I estimate the preference parameters of the model using simulated method
 of moments inside a parallel MCMC algorithm.
 I then use the estimated model to simulate the effect of gradually decreasing
 the mortgage interest rate deduction.
 I find that mobility rates strongly respond to this change, with an elasticity
 of z%.
 Furthermore, I find that housing is an important part of explaining mobility
 over the lifecycle.
 Owners have significantly higher mobility costs than similar renters.
\end_layout

