 In essence, this is a likelihood free estimator which employs what is called
 parallel tempering, i.e.
 several Monte Carlo chains that evolve in parallel and at different 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

temperatures
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 with different variances of the shock used to generate new parameter guesses).
 The key is that the chains are allowed to communicate at random times,
 such that if for example a hot (high variance) chain explored and area
 of the parameter space with relatively small function evaluations, cooler
 chains can jump to that region.
 This is an advantage in problems with multiple local optima and non-differentia
bilities, such as the one at hand.
 Furthermore, the parallel setup of the estimator lends itself almost naturally
 to large computer clusters, where each compute node is a chain.
